The HD 74156 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HD 74156 is a star with 1.24 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.48 times its radius. It is located 187.88 light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 3.7 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

HD 74156 is known to have 2 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HD 74156 system


HD 74156 b

HD 74156 b was discovered by the Haute-Provence Observatory observatory, in 2004-01, using the radial velocity method. Its semi-major axis is 0.29 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HD 74156 b is 572.400 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HD 74156 b is 13.400 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, HD 74156 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.


HD 74156 c

HD 74156 c was discovered by the Haute-Provence Observatory observatory, in 2004-01, using the radial velocity method. Its semi-major axis is 3.85 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HD 74156 c is 2563.080 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HD 74156 c is 12.600 that of Earth. At more than 50 Earth masses, HD 74156 c is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
